    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'll try tracemalloc then. i've heard people call it a \"leak\" because it feels like bits of it are just disappearing into nowhere. is there any way to actually pin down the specific object or function that's responsible for that constant increase? like, how do i find the culprit causing the drain?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Pinpointing the culprit is all about tracing the lineage of that memory. When `tracemalloc` shows you a growing block, you need to look at the stack trace associated with that allocation. It tells you exactly which line of code called the function that created that object.\n\nIf you're using generators, make sure you aren't accidentally holding onto references to the generator object itself or intermediate results outside the loop. Sometimes, a poorly managed closure or a global variable that gets updated in every iteration can hold onto a reference, making the garbage collector think that memory is still needed. Look for objects that are being created inside your loop but never explicitly deleted or allowed to go out of scope.",
      "source": "target",
